</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,684,385,719]" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">
<taxonomicName box="[177,422,386,412]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ehretiaceae" genus="Hilsenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schatziana">
<emphasis box="[177,422,386,412]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">Hilsenbergia schatziana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is apparently a substrate specialist restricted to northern 
<collectingCountry box="[506,634,417,443]" name="Madagascar" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
and is distinct from other members of the genus in its large fruits, glabrous leaves, c. 7 × 
<quantity box="[530,596,477,503]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" unit="mm" value="7.0">7 mm</quantity>
corolla, and in lacking bracts in its inflorescence. It is named in honor of my colleague George SCHATZ, a leading authority on the flora of 
<collectingCountry box="[548,680,570,596]" name="Madagascar" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
, who’s guide to the woody plant genera, and numerous other publications, have contributed so much to our understanding of the systematics and evolution of Malagasy plants.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="188" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,684,753,1087]" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">
DISTRIBUTION. — 
<taxonomicName box="[396,658,754,780]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ehretiaceae" genus="Hilsenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schatziana">
<emphasis box="[396,658,754,780]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">Hilsenbergia schatziana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from only four collections, all from northern 
<collectingCountry box="[273,419,815,841]" name="Madagascar" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[440,536,815,841]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="30.[714,743,1084,1101]" captionTargetBox="[768,1210,175,1042]" captionTargetId="figure-561@30.[659,1217,171,1046]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="Fig. 14. — Distributions of Hilsenbergia species, mapped on the simplified bioclimate zones of Madagascar (after CORNET 1974; see SCHATZ 2000)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5181051" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5181051/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). It may be restricted to basalt.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,684,753,1087]" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">
CONSERVATION STATUS. — Provisional IUCN Red List Category: Endangered (EN B2ab(i-iv)). 
<taxonomicName box="[151,402,938,964]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ehretiaceae" genus="Hilsenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="37" pageNumber="188" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schatziana">
<emphasis box="[151,402,938,964]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">Hilsenbergia schatziana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from only two populations in northern 
<collectingCountry box="[452,593,969,995]" name="Madagascar" pageId="37" pageNumber="188">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
, one of which occurs within Montagne d’Ambre National Park, and it has not been collected for nearly 50 years.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
